---
import Layout from '../_layouts/DocumentationLayout.astro';

const metadata = {
  title: {
    default: 'Typography',
  },
};
---

<Layout
  metadata={metadata}
  headline={{
    tagline: 'Base',
    title: 'Typography',
    subtitle: 'Fluid responsive typography system using clamp() for seamless scaling',
  }}
>
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2>Headings</h2>

    <h1>Heading 1</h1>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted">
      <strong>clamp(2rem, 1.5rem + 2vw, 3rem)</strong> 32px → 48px | Line height: 1.2
    </p>

    <h2>Heading 2</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted">
      <strong>clamp(1.75rem, 1.5rem + 1.25vw, 2.25rem)</strong> 28px → 36px | Line height: 1.25
    </p>

    <h3>Heading 3</h3>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted">
      <strong>clamp(1.5rem, 1.35rem + 0.75vw, 1.875rem)</strong> 24px → 30px | Line height: 1.3
    </p>

    <h4>Heading 4</h4>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted">
      <strong>clamp(1.25rem, 1.15rem + 0.5vw, 1.5rem)</strong> 20px → 24px | Line height: 1.3
    </p>

    <h5>Heading 5</h5>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted"><strong>1.125rem (fixed)</strong> 18px | Line height: 1.4</p>

    <h6>Heading 6</h6>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted"><strong>1rem (fixed)</strong> 16px | Line height: 1.4</p>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2>Body Text</h2>

    <h3>Paragraph</h3>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted mb-4">
      <strong>clamp(1rem, 0.95rem + 0.25vw, 1.125rem)</strong>16px → 18px | Line height: 1.6
    </p>
    <p>
      The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog. This is a sample paragraph to demonstrate the
      fluid typography system. The font size scales smoothly between viewport widths, eliminating
      the awkward jumps that occur with traditional breakpoint-based responsive design. This
      approach ensures optimal readability across all screen sizes.
    </p>
    <p>
      Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut
      labore et dolore magna aliqua. Ut enim ad minim veniam, quis nostrud exercitation ullamco
      laboris nisi ut aliquip ex ea commodo consequat.
    </p>

    <h3>Paragraph with Link</h3>
    <p>
      This paragraph contains a <a href="#">standard link element</a> that demonstrates the hover state
      with underline and color transition. Links are styled globally to maintain consistency across the
      entire site.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2>Lists</h2>

    <h3>Unordered List</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>First item with sufficient text to wrap</li>
      <li>Second item in the list</li>
      <li>Third item demonstrating list style</li>
      <li>Fourth item with more content to show line height behavior</li>
      <li>Fifth item completing the example</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Ordered List</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>First step in the process</li>
      <li>Second step with description</li>
      <li>Third step demonstrating sequence</li>
      <li>Fourth step in the ordered list</li>
      <li>Fifth and final step</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2>Font Families</h2>

    <h3>Title Font (Kodchasan)</h3>
    <p class="font-title text-2xl">The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog. 0123456789</p>

    <h3>Subtitle Font (Quicksand)</h3>
    <p class="font-subtitle text-2xl">The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog. 0123456789</p>

    <h3>Body Font (Quicksand)</h3>
    <p class="font-body text-2xl">The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog. 0123456789</p>

    <h3>Quote Font (Sacramento)</h3>
    <p class="font-quote text-3xl">The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog. 0123456789</p>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2>Content Sample</h2>
    <article class="prose max-w-none">
      <h3>The Importance of Typography in Web Design</h3>
      <p>
        Typography is one of the most critical aspects of web design. It affects not only the
        aesthetic appeal of your website but also its usability and accessibility. Good typography
        enhances readability, establishes hierarchy, and creates a pleasant reading experience.
      </p>

      <h4>Key Principles</h4>
      <p>When implementing typography systems, consider these fundamental principles:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Maintain consistent line heights for comfortable reading</li>
        <li>Use fluid scaling to adapt to different viewport sizes</li>
        <li>Establish clear visual hierarchy through size and weight</li>
        <li>Ensure sufficient contrast between text and background</li>
        <li>Optimize line length for readability (45-75 characters)</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Responsive Typography</h4>
      <p>
        Modern web design demands responsive typography that adapts seamlessly to various screen
        sizes. Traditional media query breakpoints create abrupt size changes, while fluid
        typography using CSS <code>clamp()</code> provides smooth scaling across all viewport widths.
      </p>

      <blockquote>
        Good typography makes the reading experience effortless and enjoyable, allowing content to
        speak for itself without distraction.
      </blockquote>

      <h5>Implementation Details</h5>
      <p>The typography system on this page uses the following approach:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Base font size scales from 16px to 18px using clamp()</li>
        <li>Headings scale proportionally with viewport width</li>
        <li>Line heights are optimized for each text element</li>
        <li>Font families are assigned semantic roles (title, body, quote)</li>
      </ol>

      <h6>Testing Different Viewports</h6>
      <p>
        Resize your browser window to see how the typography scales smoothly without any abrupt
        jumps. The fluid system ensures optimal readability at every size, from mobile devices at
        320px width to large desktop displays at 1920px and beyond.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Text Alignment</h2>

    <h3>Left Aligned (Default)</h3>
    <p class="text-left">
      This paragraph demonstrates left alignment, which is the default for body text in most
      languages that read from left to right. It provides the most natural reading experience.
    </p>

    <h3>Center Aligned</h3>
    <p class="text-center">
      This paragraph demonstrates center alignment, often used for headlines, taglines, or
      decorative text. Use sparingly for body content as it reduces readability.
    </p>

    <h3>Right Aligned</h3>
    <p class="text-right">
      This paragraph demonstrates right alignment, less common in Western languages but useful for
      specific design contexts or languages that read from right to left.
    </p>
  </section>
</Layout>
